/v31/n12/full/nbt.2727.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>) do offer a way of getting high-quality complex genome assemblies using only sequencing data. <\/p>\n","answer_id":13948,"question_id":13819,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13819/how-easy-is-it-to-carry-out-de-novo-sequence-assembly","last_activity_date":1386876874,"creation_date":1386257834,"answer_count":3,"title":"How easy is it to carry out de novo sequence assembly?","body":"<p>Today a colleague of mine asked the following question:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\" Assuming I need to build from 0, a chromosome of a fish, with short reads\n  but no other reference whatsoever <strong>[de novo assembly]<\/strong>:<\/p>\n  \n  <ul>\n  <li>how much work is that?  <\/li>\n  <li>Is there a generic software (like SAMtools) that will align the reads in a\n  scaffold one can use?  <\/li>\n  <li>Basically, given a reasonably clear pipeline in terms of software, is it still blood sweat and tears or is it just a matter of getting it on a cluster?\"<\/li>\n  <\/ul>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Very grateful for any suggestions, sources of information, software etc.<\/p>\n","question_id":13819,"tags":["dna","bioinformatics","dna-sequencing","software","sequence-assembly"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":13948,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":224,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1386875961},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/09d4a8efb2fcb5f138130695f0814d35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3118,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3118/derfder","reputation":293,"display_name":"Derfder","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":2,"post_id":13905,"edited":false,"creation_date":1386695198,