ture, it's great. However to find evolutionary conserved structure MSA methods like what has been used with Rfam are a more suitable way.<\/p>\n\n<p>Since you asked for Reviews, any of Sean Eddy's Rfam updates are good. I also suggest checking out <a href=\"https://www.mendeley.com/groups/545791/rna-structure/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.mendeley.com/groups/545791/rna-structure/<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>But for now, I think <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16500677\" rel=\"nofollow\">Revolutions in RNA Secondary Structure Prediction<\/a> by David Mathews who developed the Turner rules and Mfold is a good start.<\/p>\n","answer_id":13907,"question_id":13783,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13783/finding-rna-loops","last_activity_date":1386714304,"creation_date":1386103319,"answer_count":1,"title":"Finding RNA Loops","body":"<p>I was rooting through the literature, but there is too much work on the topic of detecting loops in RNA and the RNA helices that go with them.  Can anyone point to a good review on this topic or even better describe some better performing algorithms? <\/p>\n","question_id":13783,"tags":["bioinformatics","rna","structure-prediction"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":60,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/anIxF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3657,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3657/katz","reputation":424,"display_name":"Katz","accept_rate":70},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/752972781/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":4860,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4860/martink","reputation":138,"display_name":"MartinK"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackex