matic, frontal, maxilla, sphenoid, palatine, lacrimal and ethmoid bones.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Fa1sV.png\" alt=\"Bones of the human orbit\"><\/p>\n\n<p>The use of the word <strong>orbit<\/strong> (red) in <strong><em>orbito<\/em>&#65279;frontal cortex<\/strong> refers to the positioning of this part of the frontal cortex (green) being <em>directly behind the orbit<\/em>:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Z7EYb.png\" alt=\"Orbitofrontal cortex location\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":13887,"question_id":13858,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13858/what-does-orbital-mean-in-orbital-frontal-cortex","last_activity_date":1386586767,"creation_date":1386410340,"answer_count":3,"title":"What does orbital mean in orbital frontal cortex?","body":"<p>Orbital frontal cortex is where decisions are made.<\/p>\n\n<p>What does the word orbital there mean?<\/p>\n\n<p>I looked around in wikipedia and never find it.<\/p>\n","question_id":13858,"tags":["brain","human-anatomy","nomenclature"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":13861,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":867,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1386427152},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ea215e4766bf229b50b8791e2e03776d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3894,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3894/ducfabulous","reputation":180,"display_name":"DucFabulous","accept_rate":42},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/QiT7n.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3864,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3864/stella-dimitrova","reputation":218,"display_name":"Stella Dimitrova"},"score":0,"post_id":9001,"edited":false,"creation_date":1372440580,"comment_id":11629,"body":"May be the OH-group changes the summational charge of the protein (which is very important for the separation), as by adding the compound, we change pH.   Still, copper is used in electrophoresis, but as CuCl2. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2449094\" rel=\"nofollow\">ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2449094<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cb0d3bf434b794176466f428a6d681db?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4136/mys-721tx","reputation":105,"display_name":"Mys_721tx"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1386495873,"creation_date":1386495359,"body":"<p>Copper hydroxide does not dissolve very well in water, which means you will have trouble soaking them into your gels. <\/p>\n\n<p>Also, even if you managed to add enough copper hydroxide beforehand (in the wells), it is unlikely that the copper(II) ions, if any existes, will travel along with the protein due to its size. (Copper hydroxide itself does not have any charge.)<\/p>\n\n<p>As for the paper Stella mentioned, the copper salts are used after electrophoresis to produce a negative image, which is exactly what you cannot do with copper hydroxide.<\/p>\n","answer_id":13871,"question_id":9001,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1386495873},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/441d686d2d0244e94465aaca2d0aa34d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5122,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5122/bubu","reputation":111,"display_name":"bubu"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1386547097,"creation_date":1386523002,"body":"<ol>\n<li>Protein electrophoresis is often done in an alkaline pH (8.6), which is not exactly nice if you want to use $Cu(OH)_2$. <\/li>\n<li>If you need quantitation, you can use Coumassie blue or Amido black. If you want sensitivity you can use silver. These existing stuff are quite OK. <\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":13877,"question_id":9001,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1386547097}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questio