d/19816701\" rel=\"nofollow\">nasal mucociliary clearance time is slower than in individuals whose nasal passages are symmetrical<\/a>. From this information one can conclude that the particles and pathogens that you inhale are getting to spend more time inside your nasal passages, thus giving the pathogens a better chance at striving and giving you sinusitis.<\/p>\n\n<p>By looking at the information above you could think that the connection between nasal septum deviation and chronic sinusitis is clear. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11859650\" rel=\"nofollow\">This literary review<\/a> however states that the correlation between a deviated nasal septum and having chronic sinusitis is still unclear.<\/p>\n","answer_id":13880,"question_id":13720,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13720/how-is-deviated-nasal-septum-related-to-cold","last_activity_date":1386529367,"creation_date":1385779918,"answer_count":1,"title":"How is deviated nasal septum related to cold","body":"<p>I have a deviated  nasal septum and I always suffer from  common cold I was just wondering how a deviated nasal septum can be the cause for chronic common cold<\/p>\n","question_id":13720,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":13880,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":143,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"Jeffrey"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user560"},"score":0,"post_id":3370,"edited":false,"creation_date":1352250678,"comment_id":7325,"body":"This is correct. It adds credibility that your experimental primary antibody is actually binding what you think it binds."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1353092189,"creation_date":1345619587,"body":"<p>I don't believe that the Isotype Control Antibody makes the antibody bind more specifically but rather ensures that your signal is specific to your antibody.<\/p>\n\n<p>The Isotype Control Antibodies tend to bind to the non-binding domain of the antibody, typically the constant (Fc) domain. By measuring the concentration of the control antibody, you can determine what percentage of your light signal comes from your primary antibody and not from non-specific binders to your light source.<\/p>\n\n<p>This is very similar to having secondary antibodies in your assay.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ebioscience.com/isotype-controls.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Random link showing that I'm not making stuff up<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":3370,"question_id":3369,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1353092189},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1352311802,"creation_date":1352311802,"body":"<p>While bobthejoe/leonardo's answers are correct, you also need to be aware of the quality and limitations of isotype controls. You need to pick your source very carefully, as extensive testing (at my former company) has shown that some isotypes stick non-specifically under certain conditions or with certain samples. For example, we found that one common isotype from a major manufacturer (I don't remember who, it might have been Jackson) stuck non-specifically to HeLa cells by immunofluorescence and flow cytometry (the chemistry in the two assays is very similar) when used with common IF and FC protocols. You should also run no-antibody and secondary-only controls to ensure that your samples are not auto-fluorescing and that the secondary antibody is not binding non-specifically to your sample. Finally, ensure that the control exactly matches the isotype of your primary - don't use a rabbit polyclonal isotype to control for a rabbit mono, don't mix IgG subtypes, etc. Good luck!<\/p>\n","answer_id":5153,"question_id":3369,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3369/isotype-control-antibodies-in-flow-cytometry","migrated_from":{"other_site":{"icon_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/chemistry/img/apple-touch-icon.png","audience":"scientists, academics, teachers and students","favicon_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/chemistry/img/favicon.ico","site_type":"main_site","logo_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/chemistry/img/logo.png","api_site_parameter":"chemistry","open_beta_date":1336435200,"site_state":"normal","related_sites":[{"site_url":"http://meta.chemistry.stackexchange.com","api_site_parameter":"meta.chemistry","name":"Chemistry Meta Stack Exchange","relation":"meta"},{"site_url":"http://chat.stackexchange.com?tab=site&host=chemistry.stackexchange.com","name":"Chat Stack Exchange","relation":"chat"}],"closed_beta_date":1335312000,"styling":{"tag_background_color":"#FFF","link_color":"#0077CC","tag_foreground_color":"#000"},"markdown_extensions":["MathJax"],"site_url":"http://chemistry.stackexchange.com","name":"Chemistry","high_resolution_icon_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/chemistry/img/apple-touch-icon@2.png","twitter_account":"StackChemistry","launch_date":1431475200},"on_date":1346158622,"question_id":991},"last_activity_date":1386525291,"creation_date":1345372578,"answer_count":2,"title":"Isotype control antibodies in Flow Cytometry","body":"<p>In a Flow Cytrometry, one can add an Isotype Control Antibody to allow another antibody to bind more specific to the cells.<\/p>\n\n<p>My question is, how can the Isotype Control Antibody add specificity to the other antibody?\nMy thought 