n of human intelligence and whether it is so unique is <a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/crux/2011/12/07/bursting-the-bubble-of-human-intelligence/#.Uk86-dLktyI\" rel=\"nofollow\">subject to debate<\/a>.  Certainly there are other primates who appear to be as or more social than we.  I think <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_human_intelligence#Models\" rel=\"nofollow\">other theories<\/a> seem as or more likely.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Darwin's theory of evolution doesn't refute many theories of how something happens in evolutionary history.  The Panspermia hypothesis is taken quite seriously at this point - could it be that life originated elsewhere then was introduced here by meteorites.  The origin of Species doesn't have a lot to say about that.  I think the same is true for the emergence of human intelligence, which at this point we believe is unique on Earth.  Hard to make an irrefutable theory based upon a single example. <\/p>\n","answer_id":10718,"question_id":10717,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1385145288},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/GqkqP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4101,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4101/amory","reputation":7383,"display_name":"Amory"},"score":6,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1381015849,"creation_date":1380925652,"body":"<p>Refute?  No.<\/p>\n\n<p>Shigeta summarized the work pretty well, and though I have my own opinions on McKenna's theory the fact is that Darwin and McKenna are <em>not<\/em> opposed.  The \"Stoned Ape theory\" is a specific idea for how human intelligence might have appeared from earlier hominids.  Darwin (and <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Russel_Wallace\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wallace<\/a>) proposed a broad theory that has borne out for the process of evolution by natural selection.  Evolution applies to populations large and small, whether human, primate, or bacterial.<\/p>\n\n<p>Evolution, however, is not particularly predictive and would say nothing about what might happen should some primates eat some entheogens.  McKenna's idea could fit into reality, although as Shigeta said it is difficult to prove, but there is technically no Darwinian reason why it couldn't have happened.  Darwin did write about human evolution in <em><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Descent_of_Man,_and_Selection_in_Relation_to_Sex\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Descent of Man<\/em><\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":10719,"question_id":10717,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1381015849},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a81a5f3abd1a56c934a6d159adb714d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":4962,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4962/user4962","reputation":1,"display_name":"user4962"},"score":-2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":13588,"edited":false,"creation_date":1385416157,"comment_id":17754,"body":"Hi, whilst I wasn&#39;t involved in the original editing of your answer please be aware that the Stack Exchange model allows <i>anyone<\/i> to submit edits for peer review.  Please refer to <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/help/editing\">this page<\/a> for further help."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a81a5f3abd1a56c934a6d159adb714d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":4962,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4962/user4962","reputation":1,"display_name":"user4962"},"score":0,"post_id":13588,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","ac