<\/strong>.  Therefore you could eliminate a large amount of your difficulties by just using these terms instead for most of the body.  <\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>To answer your specific questions:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>So I conclude that human nose is anterior<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>So I concluded that humans' top head is dorsal. Yet ...We call humans' top head anterior<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The top of the head is <em>technically<\/em> dorsal, however in practice would never really be referred to as such, instead being <strong>superior<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In humans, is humans' chin ventral from the eye too? or posterior?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The human chin is both inferior to the eye (looking straight at the face in the coronal plane) and <strong>anterior<\/strong> to the eye (but only marginally).  It's more obvious if we look at the tip of the nose instead, which again is both inferior and anterior to the eye.  <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In humans, is the nose anterior too?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes, the nose is anterior.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":13639,"question_id":13610,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13610/for-the-human-head-which-direction-is-anterior-and-which-direction-is-ventral","last_activity_date":1385305555,"creation_date":1385106857,"answer_count":1,"title":"For the human head, which direction is anterior, and which direction is ventral?","body":"<p>I read the wikipedia entry and I am sort of confused.<\/p>\n\n<p>In dog, the nose is toward the front. That's anterior. So I conclude that human nose is anterior.<\/p>\n\n<p>In dog, the head is on the back. So that's dorsal. So I concluded that humans' top head is dorsal.<\/p>\n\n<p>Yet that's not how things seem to work on anatomy.<\/p>\n\n<p>We call humans' top head anterior. We also call human nose direction as ventral.<\/p>\n\n<p>How could that be?<\/p>\n\n<p>The whole system of anterior, dorsal, ventral, posterior is there so we can see humans like we see dogs (at least anatomically).<\/p>\n\n<p>Yet it changes again.<\/p>\n\n<p>So which one is right?<\/p>\n\n<p>Let me put it this way<\/p>\n\n<p>Dog's chin is ventral from the eye\nIn humans, is humans' chin ventral from the eye too? or posterior?<\/p>\n\n<p>What about the nose? Dog's nose is it's anterior most organ.<\/p>\n\n<p>In humans, is the nose anterior too?<\/p>\n\n<p>I mean, if we're going to have different terms for humans and dogs, might as well use words like up, down, front, back right?<\/p>\n","question_id":13610,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3085,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1385305555},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/mVJzi.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4990,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4990/alchemistbd","reputation":11,"display_name":"Alchemistbd"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":0,"post_id":13638,"edited":false,"creation_date":1385302788,"comment_id":17723,"body":"What species do you mean - is it Bactrocera cucurbitae?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/mVJzi.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4990,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4990/alchemistbd","reputation":11,"display_name":"Alchemistbd"},"score":0,"post_id":13638,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1385372480,"comment_id":17740,"body":"I have mention about Bactrocera cucumis"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/13638/what-are